### 2. Optimistic Locking (Second Line of Defense — orderConsumer)

Even with partitioning, edge cases exist (rebalances, retries). The `orderConsumer` uses a **version field** to detect concurrent modifications:

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant E1 as Event A (v=3)
    participant DB as MongoDB Order
    participant E2 as Event B (v=3)
    
    E1->>DB: findOneAndUpdate WHERE version=3
    E2->>DB: findOneAndUpdate WHERE version=3
    DB-->>E1:   Updated (v→4)
    DB-->>E2:   null (version mismatch)
    E2->>DB: Re-read order (v=4)
    E2->>DB: findOneAndUpdate WHERE version=4
    DB-->>E2:   Updated (v→5)
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `orderConsumer` retries up to **5 times** on version conflicts with exponential backoff (50ms → 100ms → 200ms → 400ms → 800ms). If all retries fail, the error propagates to Kafka's DLQ.

